LIME¶

MIMUW XAI WINTER 2022/2023¶

Task¶

In this homework we used brain stroke dataset from kaggle.

Ad. 0¶

I prepared the data (onehot encoding) and first trained XGBClassifier model.The model achieved 94,6% accuracy.

Ad. 1¶

I selected some observations. All predictions were 0.

Ad. 2¶

Calculated decomposition. The results are as follows

Results from these random samples are unstable:

3/6 samples have age as a highest attribute and its consistant with result from previous homework

2/6 samples looks first for avg_glucose_level

1/6 smaples starts with hypertension

Ad. 4¶

From shap I got following results:

These results differ from these got from lime. Here we observe age as highest attribute in 5 out of 6 cases. Although avg_glucose_level is at the second place or third place in almost every sample.

Ad. 5 Comparing with different models:¶

I checked results for CatBoostClassifier and for LogisticRegression.

Results for the same sample for 3 different models are very similar to each other.

Ad. 6¶

Lime seems unstable when it comes to different samples but gives similar results across models.

Lime in compare to shap gives very different results. I expected that lime would give similar most important attribute. In ecomposition of one of samples (pictures below) we can see that age is not even among top 10 attributes in lime, but it is the highest in shap, so i am very surprised. Maybe age in the corresponding lime bucket is just not significant. It actually makes sense because we don't often hear about a man having a stroke at a young age, but more often we hear about older people who have had a stroke. When predicting brain stroke for middle age people, health condition indicators are simply more significant attributes.
